description: Latin evaginare (“to unsheath”), from ex (“from”) and vagina (“sheath”).

entries.meaning: Protruded, or grown out, as an evagination; turned inside out; unsheathed; evaginated.

verbs.description: evaginate (third-person singular simple present evaginates, present participle evaginating, simple past and past participle evaginated)

entries.meaning: (intransitive) To evert a bodily organ inside surface to outside.
(transitive) To cause (a bodily organ or part) to turn inside out.
